stylometry:
I chose my data from the Great Lakes Intercolliegiate Athletic Conference, through their website, about volleyball teams in the GLIAC.  I was curious as to where we stood statistically with the teams we were competing against.  On a more advanced level, this would be important for coaches to see where their teams stands next to others, how the competition rates, and how to prepare for further seasons.  

I had to pick out the data that I thought best determined what a solid volleyball club was. I chose six sets of data that I thought defined a "volleyball player." After getting all of the data, it was necessary for me to standardize the data.  After the standardized data was found, I had to find the squared distance to the centers.  This gave me data that was closest to the average. By standardizing the data, and finding the squared distances, it allows the data to be better clustered.  Vlookup played a big role in the determining of the clusters.  It allowed me to look up data from my original set of data, and put it into another table.  If I changed the number, the team changed along with it.  This is also where the logical upper limit came into play.  There were only 14 teams, so it was important for me to have a constraint that said it must be >=1 and <=14, otherwise I could have been looking up a non-existent team. I was able to cluster the teams into three clusters, best, average, and worst. I found the final information to be very accurate in terms of the competition in the GLIAC. 

Clustering was one of the more relateable topics for me, because I was able to conclude where we stood in the GLIAC compared to other teams.
